A valve in the cylinder shown in <image 1> has a cross-sectional area of 11 cm2 with a pressure of 735 kPa inside the cylinder and 99 kPa outside.How large a force is needed to open the valve?

A. F=689.4N
B. F=660.5N
C. F=699.6N
D. F=709.6N

To determine the force needed to open the valve, we need to calculate the net force acting on the valve due to the pressure difference between the inside and outside of the cylinder.

Given:
- Cross-sectional area of the valve, \( A_{\text{valve}} = 11 \, \text{cm}^2 = 11 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{m}^2 \)
- Pressure inside the cylinder, \( P_{\text{cyl}} = 735 \, \text{kPa} = 735 \times 10^3 \, \text{Pa} \)
- Pressure outside the cylinder, \( P_{\text{outside}} = 99 \, \text{kPa} = 99 \times 10^3 \, \text{Pa} \)

The net pressure difference across the valve is:
\[ \Delta P = P_{\text{cyl}} - P_{\text{outside}} \]

Substituting the given values:
\[ \Delta P = 735 \times 10^3 \, \text{Pa} - 99 \times 10^3 \, \text{Pa} \]
\[ \Delta P = 636 \times 10^3 \, \text{Pa} \]
\[ \Delta P = 636 \, \text{kPa} \]

The force required to open the valve is given by the product of the net pressure difference and the cross-sectional area of the valve:
\[ F = \Delta P \times A_{\text{valve}} \]

Substituting the values:
\[ F = 636 \times 10^3 \, \text{Pa} \times 11 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{m}^2 \]
\[ F = 636 \times 11 \]
\[ F = 6996 \, \text{N} \]

Therefore, the force needed to open the valve is:
\[ F = 699.6 \, \text{N} \]

So, the correct answer is:
\[ \boxed{C} \]
